description.value: Terracotta figure of seated ithyphallic Harpocrates with harp. A naked youth, modelled in the round and seated on a block resting on a low rectangular plinth; his head is turned to his right and is shaven with a side-lock. He plays a triangular harp which rests on top of his huge, horizontally projecting, phallus. His left buttock and the upper part of the block immediately below it appear to have been cut away before firing. Solid; two-piece mould. Micaceous brown Nile silt with a darker core; traces of an overall white dressing. The figure was painted pink and the harp and the block left white.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure of draped woman suckling infant. A standing woman holding a baby. She wears a chiton and a wide himation. The chiton is pulled down to expose her left breast, and her right arm is almost entirely covered by the himation, leaving her hand free to direct the breast towards the child, who is held by her left hand. Her left arm is bare from the mid upper arm, and a fold of the himation falls over her left wrist. The baby is naked and is ignoring the breast, its head nestling below it, its face half-hidden against the woman’s body: it may be asleep. The back is all but plain, the left elbow indicated; there is no vent. Hollow, from two-piece mould; the head was probably made separately and is now missing, as is part of the baby's head. There are remains of an overall white dressing; a minute trace of pink paint survives on the child’s body. Orange-brown Nile silt with a grey core, common fine mica, rounded quartz and white inclusions.

description.value: Wooden striding figure of Meryrahashtef: the figure shows the subject as a young man, probably in his teens. It is carved from a single piece of ebony and mounted on a simple base of sycamore wood. The form is conventional: the young man is shown, rather exceptionally, in the nude, striding forward, his left leg advanced, his arms at his sides, fists clenched, holding truncated cylindrical objects which have been identified as small rolls of cloth. The head is covered with the conventional curled wig, very carefully carved and painted black, and the eyes, which in a superior commission would have been inlaid, are simply painted. The delineation of the facial details is sensitive and restrained: the eyebrows are lightly indicated, the nose subtly modeled, the unemphasized mouth slightly unbalanced, suggesting a wry smile.

description.value: Terracotta reclining ithyphallic figure. A reclining naked man with receding hair and a beard, his legs extending to his right, the left bent and close to the ground, the right with the knee raised. He leans his left elbow and forearm on a pile of cushions, and his right arm and hand hold his large phallus upright against his right side and rising almost level with the top of his head. His left hand holds a small unrecognized object (a looped garland or a small pot?) against his corpulent belly. The figure is modelled in relief with a flat back and was probably made in a one piece mould; it has a low curving plinth, hollow underneath. Micaceous orange-brown Nile silt with substantial remains of a white dressing overall; there is beige paint on the face and pink paint survives in places on the legs.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure of Bes. Bes standing on the capital block of a column, naked, with his hands on his thighs; he wears a feathered headdress. The shaft of the column is broken away below its base and it’s impossible to tell how much is missing. The capital widens upwards and is undecorated, probably based on a papyrus capital. The back is plain and the crown is pierced at the top, perhaps to hold a stick of incense. Hollow, from a two-piece mould, with traces of a white dressing on the sides. Red-brown Nile silt with frequent fine gold mica and white inclusions.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure group fragment. Small fragment of a dancing group: probably a maenad and a satyr. The woman, whose right leg is extended somewhat to her right, appears to wear only a himation, draped across her body from her left shoulder, leaving her right shoulder and breast bare: the two opposite long edges of the shawl are picked out in black paint, one edge passing near the right breast and under the right arm, the other curving down from the left shoulder, outlining her hip and the side of her upper left leg, to turn towards her right foot. Her right arm is bent, with the lost hand rising close to the right hand of the satyr: this hand is all that remains of him and his arm must have passed behind the maenad’s neck to rest on her right shoulder; a break running from her left hip to her knee indicates that he was dancing close to her left side. Hollow, from two-piece mould. The himation and the satyr’s hand are covered with a red slip; the black edges of the garment may be a fired on ceramic colour, or may be post-firing paint; some black specks remain near the satyr’s hand. Red-brown Nile silt, with abundant fine gold mica, quartz and white inclusions.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure of dwarf carrying basket. A dwarf workman, probably a fisherman, wearing an exomis over a short-sleeved garment, standing on a tall, flat-faced plinth. His face tends towards the grotesque and he has a full head of hair, with a side-lock falling on to his right shoulder. A basket at his waist is slung from his left shoulder, but his raised right arm, which was probably but not certainly produced in the mould, is largely lost. The back is plain, with a circular vent. Hollow, from two-piece mould. Orange-brown Nile silt with abundant fine gold mica and some white inclusions.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta relief plaque of goddess. A plaque in the form of a shrine, with a triangular pediment once containing a segment of a circle, and an architrave supported by columns in the form of two standing Bes figures. Each Bes is naked, with his hands on his thighs; their tall feathered crowns (the feathers are not defined) rise up to the architrave. A small architectural moulding projects from the outer side of each crown and turns upwards at right angles to support the end of the architrave. Both Bes figures stand on a plinth, in front of which is a recumbent lion with its head turned to front and its front paws crossed in an Egyptian manner. Within the shrine is a naked female deity, with her hands hanging by her sides, and wearing a short but very full wig with layered locks. She stands, and the lions rest, on a projecting ledge at the bottom of the plaque. The back is flat and the edges knife-trimmed at an angle. Made by pressing into a plaster one-piece mould. The front is covered with a thin matt red slip. Red-brown Nile silt, with a thick brown core and a large brown area on the back, abundant fine gold mica and rounded quartz, some small white inclusions.

description.value:
Fragmentary basalt figure, the body and base now missing.

The figure wears a smooth cap style of wig which is set high on the forehead. The eyebrows are thick and heavily arched, and the eyes have a thick ridge across the upper eyelids. The slightly oversized ears are carefully rendered with the earlobe pushed forward towards the face. The head is particularly enlarged and the face is rounded and fleshy in appearance at the jawline. The nose is long and very broad at the tip, while the mouth is wide with thin lips. The upper lip is flat while the lower lip is slightly curved.

In addition to the loss of the body of the figure, the edges of both ears are chipped and there are several abrasions across the top of the head. The tip of the chin has also now broken off. A large crack is also visible in the stone around the left side of the face and neck. The object is attached to a tall modern base.

description.value: Egyptian terracotta figure of Apis bull. Only small part of head survives of what was probably an Apis Bull bust. Very little survives: horns, an eyebrow and the place where the right ear is broken away. The horns rise up from the top of the head, the right one lacking its tip, as does the left horn, but this is damaged at its junction with the head. The sun’s disc is embraced by the horns, and bears on its face, in relief, a bust of Helios with a radiate crown. The rear is summarily treated. Hollow, from a two-piece mould. Covered with an overall white dressing and bearing considerable areas of post-firing colour at the front: the bull’s head and horns are painted yellow, the flesh parts of Helios are pink, and traces of blue paint survive on the crown. Red-brown Nile silt with a brown surface and grey core. Fine gold mica and white inclusions visible.

description.value: Terracotta figure of Osiris-Canopus, incorporating a small lamp in the plinth. The head wears a 'nemes' headdress, with uraeus on the brow, surmounted by the horns, leaves and disc of the atef crown. A rectangular bulla hangs on the chest by a cord round the shoulders; below the cord are two large circular impressions. The back has no detail, and a circular depression is situated in its centre. Brown, micaceous clay; details of face, headdress and the bulla cord picked out in black; traces of white on headdress, crown and bulla; these pigmentation details are probably of post-firing application.

description.value: Head of terracotta female figure.  A woman's head broken from a figure; the hair is arranged in the melon style, with a deep central parting, drawn back to a large ring-shaped bun.  Mould-made, with much hand-tooling; the bun has been added, and the join between the head and the neck is noticeable: the neck was probably made separately to affix the head to the lost body. Micaceous orange-brown Nile silt, with minute traces of a white dressing; traces of pink paint remain in the join between the head and the neck.
